item.title: European Union Sets Out $824 Billion Virus Recovery Plan
item.description: The plan comes alongside a $1.2 trillion budget proposal, aimed at lifting the region from its economic slump, and threatens to intensify the political fights already dividing the bloc.

item.title: Hong Kong Protesters Meet With Fierce and Swift Riot Police Squads
item.description: Thousands joined demonstrations across Hong Kong to oppose a bill that would criminalize disrespect of China’s national anthem, as well as a national security law that Beijing has vowed to impose on the city.

item.title: India's Migrants Head Home as Lockdown Eases, Prompting Fears of Spread
item.description: More than 10 million of India’s suddenly jobless migrant workers are moving from cities back to their home villages, a historic reverse-migration that brings with it concerns about a new wave of coronavirus cases and social unrest in some of the poorest, least prepared places.

item.title: Brazil's Daily Coronavirus Death Toll Surpasses That of U.S.
item.description: Brazil has reached a grim milestone, reporting more Covid-19 deaths in one day than the U.S., which until recently had logged the most daily fatalities from the disease.

item.title: Italy Reopens but Milan's Chinese Follow a Cautious Path
item.description: The country’s large Chinese community began locking down before the official quarantine began, and it is slower to exit, too

item.title: Geopolitical Power Play Over Coronavirus Vaccine Leaves Drugmakers in the Middle
item.description: Pharmaceutical companies are bracing for export bans on future coronavirus vaccines and spreading production across different continents, on early signs of a high-stakes geopolitical scramble to secure supplies for a scientific breakthrough that could confer enormous economic and political power.
